{"id":"1702.01771","submitter":"Stuart Barth","authors":"Stuart Barth and Ashwin K. Iyer","title":"On the Unique Determination of Modal Multiconductor Transmission-Line\n  Properties","comments":"10 pages, 3 figures","journal-ref":"IEEE Access, Vol. 8, 2020","doi":"10.1109/ACCESS.2020.3042435","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.class-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Some modal (or decoupled) transmission-line properties such as\nper-unit-length impedance, admittance, or characteristic impedance have long\nbeen held to be, in general, non-unique. This ambiguity arises from the nature\nof the similarity transformations used to relate the terminal and modal\ndomains, for which the voltage transformation matrix has been shown to be only\nloosely related to the corresponding current transformation matrix. Modern\nmethods have attempted to relate the two, but these relations typically rely on\narbitrary normalizations, leading to strictly incorrect and/or non-unique\nresults. This work introduces relations between the two transformations,\nderived from the physical equivalence of total power and currents between the\ntwo domains, by which the transformation matrices can be unambiguously related\nto each other, and the modal properties uniquely solved. This technique allows\nfor the correct extraction of the modal transmission-line properties for any\narbitrary system of conductors. Multiple examples are studied to validate the\nproposed solution process.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 6 Feb 2017 19:18:33 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-12-17"}
